Cleaning text

Barplot of Corpus

This is a bar plot of the corpus and includes the frequency of an individual words occurance.

#Barplot
w <- rowSums(tdm)
w <- subset(w, w>= 15)
barplot(w,
        las = 2,
        col = rainbow(5))

Wordcloud of Corpus

This visual shows the frequency of occurence by displaying words with higher frequency in larger text and towards the center, and words with lower frequency spiraling out towards the edge of the word cloud and in smaller text.

#wordcloud
library(wordcloud)
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
w <- sort(rowSums(tdm), decreasing = TRUE)
set.seed(222)
wordcloud(words = names(w),
          freq = w,
          random.color = FALSE,
          random.order = FALSE,
          colors = brewer.pal(8, 'Set2'),
          scale = c(5, 0.3),
          rot.per = .15)

Wordcloud # 2

This word cloud is interactive, allowing you to hover over any given word and displaying how often the word occurs in our data set.

#wordcloud2
library(wordcloud2)
w <- data.frame(names(w), w)
colnames(w) <- c('word', 'freq')
wordcloud2(w,
           size = 0.5,
           shape = 'triangle',
           rotateRatio = 0.25,
           minSize = 1,
           color = 'random-light')

Sentiment Analysis By using the Syuzhet package, here we will conduct a sentiment analysis of the comments of Tears in heaven. We will be using the get_nrc_sentiment function here to do our sentiment analysis. Here is a brief description for this function found here directly on the r-project website.https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/syuzhet/vignettes/syuzhet-vignette.html

“The get_nrc_sentiment implements Saif Mohammad’s NRC Emotion lexicon. According to Mohammad, “the NRC emotion lexicon is a list of words and their associations with eight emotions (anger, fear, anticipation, trust, surprise, sadness, joy, and disgust) and two sentiments (negative and positive)” (See http://www.purl.org/net/NRCemotionlexicon). The get_nrc_sentiment function returns a data frame in which each row represents a sentence from the original file. The columns include one for each emotion type was well as the positive or negative sentiment valence. The example below calls the function using the simple twelve sentence example passage stored in the s_v object from above.One the data has been returned, it can be accessed as you would any other data frame. The data in the columns (anger, anticipation, disgust, fear, joy, sadness, surprise, trust, negative, positive) can be accessed individually or in sets."

#Sentiment analysis
library(syuzhet)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)
library(reshape2)
library(dplyr)

#read file
heaven <- read.csv(file.choose(), header = T)
comments <- iconv(heaven$Comment, to = 'latin1')

Here we will take a look at the sentiment score for a few comments. We take a closer look at the 5th comment and then take an indivual look at the sentiment score for two of the words that occur in that comment. We can see how the words death, and crying affect the overall sentiment score for that comment.

#obtain sentiment scores
s <- get_nrc_sentiment(comments)
head(s)
